      "\n   - `j ≠ i`, and `¬(j < i)`, thus we are in the `else` branch, and deduce `i < j`, hence `ω ⟨(i,j), ...⟩`.\n3. `j < i`: then `(wignerMatrixMap n ω) i j` is in the `else` branch, deduce `j < i`, hence `ω ⟨(j,i), ...⟩`, and `(wignerMatrixMap n ω) j i` is in `if j < i`, hence also `ω ⟨(j,i), ...⟩`.\n\nThus, we can proceed as follows:\n\n1. Check if `i = j`: then both sides are the same.\n2. If `i ≠ j`, then either `i < j` or `j < i` (because of linear order).\n   - If `i < j`: then `(wignerMatrixMap n ω) i j = ω ⟨(i,j), ...⟩`, and `(wignerMatrixMap n ω) j i` is `ω ⟨(i,j), ...⟩`.\n   - If `j < i`: then `(wignerMatrixMap n ω) i j = ω ⟨(j,i), ...⟩`, and `(wignerMatrixMap n ω) j i = ω ⟨(j,i), ...⟩`.\n\n#### Formal Proof\n\nHere is how we can formalize this in Lean:\n\n1. Use `lt_trichotomy i j` to get `i < j`, `i = j`, or `j < i`.\n2. For each case:\n   - `i = j`: both sides are `ω ⟨(i,i), ...⟩`.\n   - `i < j`: the left side is `ω ⟨(i,j), ...⟩`, and the right side also becomes `ω ⟨(i,j), ...⟩`.\n   - `j < i`: the left side is `ω ⟨(j,i), ...⟩`, and the",
