      "by sorry\n  rcases h with (h | h | h)\n  · sorry  -- Case i < j\n  · sorry  -- Case i = j\n  · sorry  -- Case j < i",
      "\n   - If `i < j`:\n     - LHS becomes `ω ⟨(i, j), ...⟩`.\n     - For RHS (`j i`):\n       - `j ≠ i`\n       - `¬(j < i)` (because `i < j`)\n       - Hence, RHS becomes `ω ⟨(i, j), ...⟩`.\n   - Similarly, if `j < i`, then:\n     - LHS becomes `ω ⟨(j, i), ...⟩`.\n     - For RHS (`j i`):\n       - `j < i`, so RHS becomes `ω ⟨(j, i), ...⟩`.\n\n### Formal Proof in Lean\n\nWe now translate this strategy into Lean. \n\nFirst, we have `i j : Fin n`. \n\n1. We perform case analysis on whether `i = j`.\n   - If `i = j`, then both sides become `ω ⟨(i, i), ...⟩`.\n2. If `i ≠ j`, we then consider whether `i < j`.\n   - If `i < j`, then:\n     - LHS becomes `ω ⟨(i, j), ...⟩`.\n     - For RHS, since `i < j`, we have `j ≠ i`, and `¬(j < i)` (by `lt_irrefl` and `lt_asymm`), so it becomes `ω ⟨(i, j), ...⟩`.\n   - If `¬(i < j)`, then because `i ≠ j`, it must be that `j < i`, because the order on `Fin n` is linear (i.e., `i < j` or `j < i` or `i = j`). \n\nHowever, Lean's `Fin n` is ordered with the derived order from `ℕ`, but in Lean, the fact that either `i < j`, `i = j`, or `j < i` for `Fin n` follows from the fact that it is a linear order (which it is, since it is a finite type with the order from `ℕ`).\n\nThus, if `i ≠ j`, we either have `i < j` or `j < i`. \n\nBut in Lean's function, we have `i < j`, otherwise, we have `i > j` (since we eliminate `i = j`).\n\nBut in Lean, we don't have `i > j` directly, but we have `¬(i < j)` and `i ≠ j`, which implies `j < i`.\n\nTherefore, the proof can go as follows:\n\n1. If `i = j`, then both sides are `ω ⟨(i, i), ...⟩`.\n2. If `i ≠ j`:\n   - Case 1: `i < j`.\n     - LHS: `ω ⟨(i, j), ...⟩`.\n     - RHS: because `i < j`, then `j ≠ i`, and `¬(j < i)`, so it becomes `ω ⟨(i, j), ...⟩`.\n   - Case 2: `¬(i < j)` (and `i ≠ j`). This implies `j < i`. Then:\n     - LHS: because `¬(i < j)` and `i ≠ j`, we are in the else case, hence `ω ⟨(j, i), ...⟩`.\n     - RHS: since `j < i`, we get `ω ⟨(j, i), ...⟩`.\n\nBut for Case 2, in Lean, it is not immediately clear that `¬(i < j)` and `i ≠ j` implies `j < i`, because `i < j` is `i.val < j.val`, but `Fin n` may have `i.val = n - 1`, and `j.val = 0`, so `¬(i < j)` but",
